{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47b9a4ee-9814-4582-b056-9743f742351d","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen a real implementation delegates to `System.IO`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nIn your classes, inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. In tests, mock or stub it.\n\n**Alternatively**, use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` and a `MockFileSystem` out of the box, saving you from writing your own wrappers.\n\n```\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"815edd34-9190-4b44-8488-173c3be265f7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their project and want to know how to make them testable.\n\nThis is a general software engineering advice question, not a code change request. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":386,"requestId":"042A:1EAE:3C6E18:4FC7BA:69E827D5"},"id":"7e196100-424b-4a8f-a3f2-a154eee18e3d","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:43:57.261Z","parentId":"cebcc221-d235-4b5f-9c53-d1f5384d64ee"}
